<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="386" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1135,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1135,1160]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Dorsocentrals 
<number box="[449,462,1136,1160]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="3.0">3</number>
+ 
<number box="[480,496,1136,1160]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="4.0">4</number>
. Wings very broad and dark brown in males, with a remarkable brown suffusion along sides of all veins in females. Pilosity denser than in the other species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1135,2030]" box="[201,668,1208,1232]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383">
Male. Body length: 
<quantity box="[424,507,1208,1232]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" unit="mm" value="13.0">13 mm</quantity>
; wing: 
<quantity box="[589,668,1208,1232]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" unit="mm" value="15.0">15 mm</quantity>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1135,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383">General coloration. Ground color dark brown with gray pollinosity; frons dark gray; fronto-orbital plate and gena gray, with silver pollinosity. Dorsum of mesonotum gray with four dark gray vittae. Calypters and halter whitish. Wing dark brown with hyaline spots. All femora gray and tibiae shining black. Abdominal tergites dorsally with faint brown spots and gray laterally.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1135,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383">
Head. Male dichoptic. Frontal row with 
<number box="[670,698,1388,1412]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="10.0">10</number>
setae each side. Fronto-orbital plate covered with cilia. Ocellar plate short. Ocellar setae long and ocellar cilia long and hooked at apex. Antenna short, not reaching the epistome; postpedicel slightly larger than pedicel. Arista with short pubescence. Palpus cylindrical. Parafacial with cilia. Cheeks upwards projected.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1135,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383">
Thorax. Proepimeral seta developed and upward directed. Dorsocentral setae 
<number box="[1165,1178,1532,1556]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="3.0">3</number>
+ 
<number box="[1196,1212,1532,1556]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="4.0">4</number>
; prosternum bare; notopleurals 
<number box="[296,313,1568,1592]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="2.0">2</number>
; anepimeron bare; katepimeron with covering cilia; katepisternals 
<number box="[1055,1066,1568,1592]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="1.0">1</number>
+ 
<number box="[1084,1101,1568,1592]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="2.0">2</number>
. scutellum with covering cilia and one pair of basal, subbasal, subapical, apical and discal setae. Prealar setae absent. Wings very large; dm-cu longer than in the other species; veins R 
<number box="[608,616,1655,1669]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="1.0">1</number>
bare apically on dorsal surface; dorsal and ventral surfaces of the radial node bare. M and R 
<number box="[411,419,1694,1708]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="4.0">4</number>
+ 
<number box="[428,435,1694,1708]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="5.0">5</number>
divergent to apex. Legs with intense pilosity; all femora with anteroventral and posteroventral rows of setae; hind tibia with anterodorsal and posterodorsal rows of setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1135,2030]" box="[201,824,1753,1777]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383">
Abdomen. Elliptic with intense pilosity. Sternite 
<number box="[748,762,1753,1777]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="1.0">1</number>
bare.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1135,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383">
Terminalia. Hypandrium plate-like. Aedeagus apex slender; distiphallus complex with sclerotized structure and distal membrane developed; gonopod relatively short and paramere developed and subpointed (
<figureCitation box="[1261,1329,1825,1849]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1974,1997]" captionTargetBox="[359,1225,210,1955]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[359,1235,193,1955]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 6. Exsul singularis Hutton: 2 — hypandrium; 3 — sternite 5; 4 — cercal plate; 5 — ovipositor, dorsal view; 6 — ovipositor, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/223967/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="383">
Fig. 
<number box="[1313,1329,1825,1849]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
). Sternite 
<number box="[151,165,1862,1886]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="5.0">5</number>
setulose, subquadrangular (
<figureCitation box="[478,546,1862,1886]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1974,1997]" captionTargetBox="[359,1225,210,1955]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[359,1235,193,1955]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 6. Exsul singularis Hutton: 2 — hypandrium; 3 — sternite 5; 4 — cercal plate; 5 — ovipositor, dorsal view; 6 — ovipositor, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/223967/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="383">
Fig. 
<number box="[530,546,1862,1886]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Cercal plate developed with posterior concavity (
<figureCitation box="[1118,1188,1862,1886]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1974,1997]" captionTargetBox="[359,1225,210,1955]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[359,1235,193,1955]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 6. Exsul singularis Hutton: 2 — hypandrium; 3 — sternite 5; 4 — cercal plate; 5 — ovipositor, dorsal view; 6 — ovipositor, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/223967/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="383">
Fig. 
<number box="[1171,1188,1862,1886]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1135,2030]" box="[201,632,1897,1921]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383">
Female. Length: 
<quantity box="[391,471,1897,1921]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" unit="mm" value="11.0">11 mm</quantity>
, wing: 
<quantity box="[553,632,1897,1921]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="1" pageNumber="383" unit="mm" value="13.0">13 mm</quantity>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1135,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="383">Similar to male, differing as follows: wings not as broad as in males and not dark brown. All veins with a remarkable brown suffusion along their length. Legs without intense pilosity; fore and hind tibia with a posterior median seta.</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1368,1996,2019]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/223966/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="384" targetBox="[223,1359,204,1967]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1368,1996,2019]" box="[151,1368,1996,2019]" pageId="2" pageNumber="384">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1996,2019]" pageId="2" pageNumber="384">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
Dorsal habitus of males of A— 
<taxonomicName authority="Hutton" authorityName="Hutton" box="[598,842,1997,2019]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Exsul" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="384" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis box="[598,761,1997,2019]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="384">Exsul singularis</emphasis>
Hutton
</taxonomicName>
; B— 
<taxonomicName authority="Malloch" authorityName="Malloch" box="[894,1111,1997,2019]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Exsul" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="384" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis box="[894,1016,1997,2019]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="384">Exsul tenuis</emphasis>
Malloch
</taxonomicName>
; C— 
<taxonomicName box="[1163,1305,1997,2019]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Exsul" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="384" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alfredoi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1163,1305,1997,2019]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="384">Exsul alfredoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1311,1368,1997,2018]" pageId="2" pageNumber="384" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/223967/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="385" targetBox="[359,1225,210,1955]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1435,1974,2027]" pageId="3" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,318,1974,1997]" pageId="3" pageNumber="385">FIGURES 2–6.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Hutton" authorityName="Hutton" box="[329,581,1974,1996]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Exsul" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis box="[329,497,1974,1996]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="385">Exsul singularis</emphasis>
Hutton
</taxonomicName>
: 2—hypandrium; 3—sternite 5; 4—cercal plate; 5—ovipositor, dorsal view; 6— ovipositor, ventral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,464]" pageId="4" pageNumber="386">
Ovipositor. Moderately long, with large tergites with setae on posterior margins. Sternite 
<number box="[1195,1209,151,175]" pageId="4" pageNumber="386" value="6.0">6</number>
broad and sternite 
<number box="[1422,1436,152,175]" pageId="4" pageNumber="386" value="7.0">7</number>
arrow-shape with five setae (
<figureCitation box="[475,573,188,212]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1974,1997]" captionTargetBox="[359,1225,210,1955]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[359,1235,193,1955]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 6. Exsul singularis Hutton: 2 — hypandrium; 3 — sternite 5; 4 — cercal plate; 5 — ovipositor, dorsal view; 6 — ovipositor, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/223967/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="386">
Fig. 
<number box="[527,573,188,212]" pageId="4" pageNumber="386" value="5.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="5.0">5–6</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,464]" pageId="4" pageNumber="386">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,264,224,248]" pageId="4" pageNumber="386">Note.</emphasis>
The general appearance of this species is very peculiar, differing from all others muscids by the large and dark wings of male.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
